        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Rothrock’s name, ‘care of Prof. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1957.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Asa Gray</ref>, Cambridge Mass.’, appears on CD’s presentation list for <hi rend="italic">Expression.</hi> CD had cited Rothrock for information on the expressions of Native Americans.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The notice has not been found in the Darwin Archive–CUL.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The passage referred to discusses actions undertaken in unconscious sympathy with other intentional or observed actions. Rothrock’s father was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6658.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Abraham Rothrock</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2401.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 36, a note was added: ‘An American physician states, in a letter to the author, that while attending women in labour he sometimes finds himself imitating the muscular efforts of the patient. This case is of interest because habit is necessarily excluded.’</note>
